From: vyos-ls1046a-build M3-3 step 2a <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-27
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: af_xdp_pool - distribute qband NAPI across online CPUs

M3-3 step 2a (first reviewable slice of spec sec 5.2 step 2 "Per-CPU
NAPI + dedicated BMan channels").  Single minimal behavioural change
inside af_xdp_pool_xsk_pool_attach():

Patch 0080 (M3-3 step 1) populated priv->qmap[queue_id].napi with the
BSP cpu 0's per-CPU NAPI portal unconditionally - a deliberate stopgap.
With four qbands (DPAA1_XSK_MAX_QBANDS=4) and four online cores
(NR_CPUS=4 on LS1046A), every bound XSK ended up on the same NAPI on
the same QMan SWP, defeating the per-CPU portal model.  Step 2a fixes
this by distributing qbands across the available CPUs:

    target_cpu = (int)queue_id % num_online_cpus();

This is the simplest correct mapping:

  * queue_id 0 -> cpu 0 (cluster 0)
  * queue_id 1 -> cpu 1 (cluster 0)
  * queue_id 2 -> cpu 2 (cluster 1)
  * queue_id 3 -> cpu 3 (cluster 1)

LS1046A's CCI-400 fabric (spec sec 4.7) groups cores 0-1 and 2-3 into
two clusters.  The trivial modulo mapping above keeps the first two
qbands on cluster 0 and the last two on cluster 1 - adequate for the
4-queue=4-cpu common case.  A cluster-aware refinement that explicitly
prefers same-cluster RX qband + consumer CPU is deferred to step 2c.

Per-CPU NAPI is reachable today because dpaa_eth.c's percpu_priv is
allocated via alloc_percpu(struct dpaa_percpu_priv) - every online
CPU has its own &per_cpu_ptr(priv->percpu_priv, cpu)->np.napi already
servicing that CPU's QMan SWP.  Calling napi_schedule_irqoff() against
a NAPI bound to a remote CPU is documented-safe (the schedule itself
is cross-CPU; the poll runs on the owning CPU's softirq).

Detach symmetry: af_xdp_pool_xsk_pool_detach() does not touch qmap[].
That is intentional - the NAPI pointer becomes stale only when the
underlying percpu_priv goes away on dpaa_remove(), which is strictly
after every XSK socket on the netdev has been unbound.  READ_ONCE() in
af_xdp_pool_xsk_wakeup() therefore remains safe across the netdev
lifetime; subsequent re-bind on the same queue_id overwrites the slot.

What is observable on hardware after this patch alone (versus 0080):

  * /tmp/xsk_bind_test eth4 q=0..3 with XDP_USE_NEED_WAKEUP and a
    100x sendto(MSG_DONTWAIT) burst PER queue_id.  ftrace
    napi_schedule_irqoff events MUST fire on:
      cpu 0 for q=0, cpu 1 for q=1, cpu 2 for q=2, cpu 3 for q=3
    (was: 100% on cpu 0 for every queue_id under 0080).
  * /proc/interrupts QMan portal lines 46-49 distribute across CPUs
    1:1 with the qbands you bind.
  * Existing M2-s2 100x churn loop still passes (attach_ok=detach_ok,
    zero error counters, zero RCU/WARN/oops).

What is NOT done in this patch (lands in later subpatches):

  * Dedicated BMan channels per qband (step 2b - bman_new_pool() is
    already per-qband as of 0075b, but QMan dispatch channels are
    still shared with the core driver's RX FQs).
  * Cluster-aware refinement (step 2c).
  * NAPI IRQ affinity hint (netif_set_napi_irq_affinity_hint).

No throughput change is expected on a single-queue test: there is
still no ZC RX/TX datapath.  iperf3 baseline on the DUT must stay
within noise of the M3-3 step 1 reference (~942 Mbps on RJ45 eth0).

Spec reference: specs/dpaa1-afxdp-modernization-spec.md v5.0 sec 5.2
Depends on: 0080.
---
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
index bfc1506..b39300c 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
@@ -279,10 +279,17 @@ rcu_assign_pointer(priv->xsk_pool[queue_id], pool);
  */
 {
 struct dpaa_percpu_priv *pcpu;
+int target_cpu;
+int n_online = num_online_cpus();
 
-pcpu = per_cpu_ptr(priv->percpu_priv, 0);
+if (unlikely(n_online <= 0))
+target_cpu = 0;
+else
+target_cpu = (int)queue_id % n_online;
+
+pcpu = per_cpu_ptr(priv->percpu_priv, target_cpu);
 WRITE_ONCE(priv->qmap[queue_id].napi, &pcpu->np.napi);
-WRITE_ONCE(priv->qmap[queue_id].cpu, 0);
+WRITE_ONCE(priv->qmap[queue_id].cpu, target_cpu);
 }
 
 priv->xsk_pool_attach_ok++;
